\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 How long have you lived here? Could I have your full name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Jane. Willsher.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 And your present address?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 This one here? 10 - 10 Denison House. Farrance Street, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Are you a widow?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 And your year of marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 1920.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 When were you born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 1896.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 And your birthplace?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Maroon Street. Limehouse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 How many years did you live in the house where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh I couldn't tell you that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You can't remember that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Do you remember when you first moved, your first move from the house you were born in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. Only from the time I was about - nine or ten. We lived in Mile End Road in the buildings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You think you moved there when you were about nine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 About nine, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You don't remember much about the earlier years?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You don't remember any houses you lived in much before that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 But you lived in that house in Mile End Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Mile End Road, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 From when you were eight?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 For how long?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 I don't know when my mother moved out of there but we was there some ti
me I know. And then we - she moved over - back of Guardian Angels church, I was married in that church, at the back there she moved and then - she - 'course them place - time you could get - places easy. And - I know - no, I can't remember if - she - I kn
ow she moved the back of that church, Jupps Road, it's still there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well - don't know about all of 'em, I - only - what I can remember, one brother like as I grew up. 'course all the others - and they'd
 - three sisters then. And a - and then my brother - we lived in the buildings in Marney Road and - my mother had a little place there, five and six a week. Two rooms and a little off room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 And you said your mother had some other children who you think died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes, well I didn't remember all that see, only what she told me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 How many did she say she had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 She had seventeen all told she said.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 But you only knew four?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes. And - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Were they older than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Can you remember how many years?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
My - my eldest sister who died she was like - what I can remember, she was eighty-seven, died about six or seven year ago. And - my brother - he was - he was - forty-seven when he died just after the first world wa
r. And - my sister alive now, she's eighty-one, so I'm the youngest one you see. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 How old was your father when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Sixty-one or sixty-three, I'm not sure for two years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 He was sixty-one when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh no. No. Before I was married - he died about 19 - 1918, he was - sixty-three or sixty-one then see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Do you know where your father came from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No. My mother was born over - Lambeth. She used to tell me, I don't know about my father. Born over - New Cut Amber she used to say.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Do you think your father was a Londoner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh he was a Londoner, yes. No, I don't know where he was born.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What was his occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well he was a - you know, used to drive a - one horse - cart. When he was at work
. And - he used to bring home a golden sovereign, put on my mother's table, that was her week's wages.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did he have any other jobs before this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well a day here and a day there, when he could get it he used to be out - oh - t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5650870\charrsid1926877 wo or three in the morning queu}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
ing up for when they took the men on the following morning, and - -perhaps the men in the front'd get a day's work and when his turn came he got nothing. And - he'd wander around, see if he could get a bit of work, and - he'd come home at twelve o
'clock in the day with nothing. My mother give him a bit of bread and cheese and a piece of Spanish onion to eat, then she'd go up Burdett Road and perhaps get two}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5650870\charrsid1926877  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 penn'orth of pieces, make a stew for me and my sister, and - 'cos my eldest sister, she was 
married then, but - the one alive now she was at home. And - she worked at the rope ground over Coburn Road in Bow. And I remember my mother used to make a dinner up, hot dinner, I used to take it over in two plates with a cloth over, take it over every d
ay. She only had about half hour's lunchtime. And I was at school then. 'Cos she's six years older than I am see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 So mainly your father drove a cart?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes. His last job was up Burdett Road here, under the arch, the place is still there. It was al
l stables down there and I - when I go up there any time of the week I always remember my father. But I don't know what they use them for now but - that was his last job, he used to drive this one horse - cart you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What did he carry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Timber
 and that you know. And if I had a holiday from school he'd take me down Farnborough or over Chelsea, I remember that well when I was a child, taking me out for a ride.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Can you remember how old your mother was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 My mum - when she was - oh no. She was seventy-one when she died, I know that, so -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 When did she die?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh - I had three children when she passed away. I know she was seventy-one but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Was that before the second world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You think she died before 1940?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 My son round here is forty-two, and he was five weeks old when she died, how would that - she's been dead forty - forty-odd years now.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Where did she come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Dambeth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Had she had any jobs before she married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh - oh I don't know about before she married, I - can't say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did she work after she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
No, she used to tell me that she was - had a nice house at Walthamstow, she - my father was his own governor in the coal business, you know, my father 
had - men working for him and - and they robbed him, you know, he used to like a drop of drink, they used to rob him and that and he - he lost all his money like that. She used to tell me all that you know. She -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 That was her father?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes. My fa
ther. My father. And - she'd say, I never - when I was a child she'd say I've never been - always been like this, poor. I've been - I've had plenty of money, had - someone do her work, someone do her washing and that, but - she used to tell me a lot, my m
other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 That was in her early years was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Yes. Like - when I can remember, about nine or ten year old she used to tell me all that, yes. She used to take in washing. I've known her be up all night doing washing up and down the board and - hangin
g the washing up on all the pictures all round the room. She would say to me, we're going to have different pictures tonight, and - me and my dad used to walk to - from Mile End right to Aldgate - couldn't afford a penny on the tram, used to be horse}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5650870\charrsid1926877 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 trams
. And - two Jewish ladies up there in Wentworth Street near the market - take the washing up there, shilling a dozen my mother used to get for that. And - used to mangle 'em and that. And - used to - they used to give us a penny extra, we used to ride bac
k
 on the tram. And she'd spend that - two shillings, like each bundle, might be a dozen and a half in each bundle, all depended, she used to get me a bit of breakfast and - and something for dinner. We never starved, although it was very hard. She was a go
od mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Can you remember her doing any other jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Who?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Your mother, besides the laundry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
No, washing. Washing. She used to tell me that in the - before I was born she used to go around with doctors delivering babies. She used to li
ke some - never belonged to anywhere but she used to go - with these doctors and bring babies in the world. But I say with my children she lost her never, she'd say, I' can't do that now. She'd do anything in my place, she'd look after me, I had nurses an
d doctors but - I can't bring babies now in the world, my - nerve's gone, but - she used to do all that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 If she bought washing into the house would she do that in the mornings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well - she'd stop up late - perhaps during the night and do it. She worked very hard my mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 How many times a week do you think she did this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Well - all different people you see round - that could - well afford to have their washing done, they used to give it to her to do. But Aldgate was the two ladies up the
re - we used to take the washing to, up in the Buildings they had, Wentworth Street. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 I'd like to ask about life at home when you were a child, do you remember how many rooms there were in the house at Mile End Road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Two, and a little off 
room. And my brother, as he got older and become engaged, the - he asked my mother could he store some - things in this little off room. She said, yes, so she gave him - he used to give her one and - one and six a week towards the rent, she paid the four 
shilling, he give her the one and six a week rent, to make up the five - five and six. And - he had them things in there 'til he got married and I was about ten years of age then, I remember that so well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did anyone else besides your parents and brothers and sisters live in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No lodgers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No relatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 My mother never had lodgers. Was only a - three rooms, two and a small one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did your mother ever pay anyone to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. She couldn't afford it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Was your washing done at home or was it sent out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes. Always at home, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did your mother or father mend or make the family clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well my mother used to make - something for me, she'd - she'd buy a big shirt, wash 
it - very clean, and - she'd make me a frock. And I had to wear that all the week, that frock, only plain, and I always wore a white pinafore every morning, a piece of white rag here for - handkerchief, off a sheet you know, she cut 'em out and - but I wa
s always kept nice and clean. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did she make her own clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Not - yes, well she had to you see, she had to - always had the needle - in her hands. Very hard working, well a lot of 'em was hard working people them days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you often have new clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No, not very often. Second}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5650870\charrsid1926877  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 hand you know, like I've had to get for my family when they were young. And }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5650870\charrsid1926877 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877  second}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5650870\charrsid1926877  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 hand boots we used to wear. And if my mother could afford it she'd save up - a few coppers and - get us something, but - ve
ry seldom - anything new.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you father or mother ever mend or make the family shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
No, he used to mend my - boots, we used to wear boots then. Used to mend mine, he - used to get a bit of leather, strong leather, and - it was off these - th
ings, I don't know what you - what the horses used to have 'em round 'em, black, we used to have one those and - he'd have his - hobbing foot and a knife and a - he'd have this }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5650870\charrsid1926877 \endash }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877  what}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5650870\charrsid1926877 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5650870\charrsid1926877  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 name and he'd mend my boot, my sister's and all, he used to do her heels and soles, couldn't afford to send 'em out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did your father help your mother with any jobs in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes, washing up or - help with a bit of dinner. Odd jobs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did he make the fires?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Any decorating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No, I don't know who did the decorating, I think the landlord had that done them days, but - not my father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did he make any improvements to the house, did he do any building or repairs in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Any little odd jobs, if he could do it he'd do it you know. But a landlord used to have more done than they do now. Places.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did he dress you or undress you or bath you, your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did he read to you or tell you stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh he'd tell me stories but - he - used to tell me all different things you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did he ever take you out without your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Now and again he would, yes, for a walk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did he ever look after you when your mother was out?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes. My mother never went out much though.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you have any tasks you had to carry out regularly at home to help your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Always helped with the - what I could do in the place bit of - housework and - when my sister started work I - I had to take her place, do the housework, and - I remember my
 mother used to put me on a - stand me on a box near a tub, we used to have the wooden tubs to do the washing in then, and they used to have a scrubbing brush to scrub the washing, rub the soap on, and - she used to let me do the tea towels and the }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5650870\charrsid1926877 handkerchiefs}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
, my mother. She used to teach me to - she said, as you grow up you'll know how to do these things, used to - let me watch her cook, like I've done all my children. I've taught them all - only plain cooking but - I - they can do anything, my children
. Yes. It doesn't hurt children I don't think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 How long did you go on doing these jobs in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 'Til I went to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Even after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes. And my dad wouldn't let me go to work before I was nearly sixteen, being the las
t one at home. He said, you stay at home and help your mother. Well then we moved - I remember - when I was nearly sixteen we lived - up in Stepney - another little house. And she paid seven shillings a week for that. And - of course as I got older I - st
a
rted courting and - got married in 1920, well - I would - yes, 1920, she was there a few years in that house, my mother. And then - and then when I started having my children I had her live with me, my mother, company. Until I had about three children, th
en she got a little room - still up Stepeny and - that's where she - lived 'til she died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did the older child help the younger, did your older brother and sister help you with anything you found difficult?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh, we all helped one another. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 They could help you with dressing and eating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh no. Not dressing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Even when you were very small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh, he may have done, yes. My mother see they took - you know - did their little jobs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you help your older brother and sister in any way?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 If I could. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What time was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well, about half past eight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did your mother or anyone else put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh no, she taught us - we had a chair at 
the side of the bed and - and - we had to undress ourself and - used to have a curtain somewhere up, and we had the chair to put our clothes on, so we always knew where to find things. She had the one routine you know, my mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 At what age did you put yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well - about - eight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you share the bedroom or the bed with any of the other children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well we had to, we only had two rooms and an off room. My - 'cos my brother got married and - and - we - we just had the room to
 live in and a - one bedroom. We had like little beds for ourself. There was a curtain like in - the middle. That's how we lived. But we were decent you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What room did you bath in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well, my mother used to have a - a tub, this tub she done h
er washing in in the - in the living room, and - my dad went out she used to - let us bath ourself like, if we had no baths to go to, public baths. Still we were always clean. My - my family, we never - I never had a bathroom 'til - not - all through my e
ight children I've had. But we was always clean, in two rooms we lived.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 How often did you have a bath when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Twice a week. All depended, if I got dirty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 When did you have clean clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 About twice a week if my mother could get 'em dry and that, she was always doing her washing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Where did the family have their meals?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well all in the one room you see, the living room. Everything was done in that room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Where did your mother cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 In the same room. We had fire ovens you know. Oven onto the fireplace and - never had no cooker. She used to use that oven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 That was using coal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes. Coke as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 When was breakfast eaten? Can you remember what time you'd have breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh we always had something to eat before I went to school. But - about eight o'clock I should imagine. Be at school at nine o'clock.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did all the family eat breakfast together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well there was - wasn't a lot of us, see my brother was married and there was only m
y sister, well then she started going to work. She had to be at work at half past six in the morning. And - that's the one I used to take the dinner to, and - there was only myself at home then. As far back as I remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What did you usually have for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well - sometimes bread and dripping. Bread and jam. But we never starved on it you know. Never had no cereals like they have now. No.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Would you have a cup of tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes, and I used to take lunch to school with me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you ever have anything different for breakfast on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well, if my mother could afford egg we had egg. All depended you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What about the midday meal, what time would you have lunch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well we always had hot - hot lunch, my mother made a lot 
of stews and that and - a pudding for afterwards. You know, and - with a - perhaps a bit of sugar on. And - we used to have condensed milk then, no cows milk. And a - but we - we never starved you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Were all the family present for this midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Well I tell you it's only my - after my brother got married there'd only my sister left at home. See, there wasn't a lot of us. My father, if he wasn't at work he'd be home but all depended see, if he got a day's work anywhere. If he was out. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What about the evening meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Oh we didn't have much - wasn't much difference to - to breakfast really you know. Bit of bread and jam or - what my mother could afford, if you had a bit of cheese and a piece. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Do you remember having a different lunch on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Oh yes, we had - used to have a nice lunch of a Sunday, you know - my mother used to - get a bit of - little bit of beef or something like that which she could afford or mutton, no lamb then, mutton. And - potatoes - used 
to be about four - four pound a penny. Fish was cheap. Kippers and that you know, the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5650870\charrsid1926877 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877  three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5650870\charrsid1926877  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 farthings a pair, two pair three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5650870\charrsid1926877  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 ha'pence or - well it had to be because there wasn't the money you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did your mother bake her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Make any jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 She used to make jam, yes. But - not her own bread.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did she bottle any fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. She'd make it and we'd eat it, when it cooled down you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did she make any pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Any wine or medicines for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Any beer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you have a garden to grow any vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. Never had nothing like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you buy vegetables and fruit?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 My mother'd buy - yes - had to buy it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What about tinned vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 See nothing like that then, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Or dried vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. Never see nothing like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 So any vegetables or fruit that you ate came from a market or a shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Everything come from the market.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you keep any livestock, any hens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
My - my dad - livestock, my dad - used to - before I got married he used to have rabbits, couple of rabbits. And - when he worked up Burdett Road - he used to go and feed his horse - every Sunday morning and - all the ot
her men didn't want to go, they used to give him four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5650870\charrsid1926877  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
pence each, I remember that well, and asked him to feed his horse and - they'd say, here you are George - buy some pints. 'Cos pints - of beer was four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5650870\charrsid1926877  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 pence. And - he wouldn't buy the beer. And he saved all the four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5650870\charrsid1926877  pence}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
 and - and - and - he'd go in the corn chandlers and buy rabbit food and - oh he loved his rabbits he had. And we used to have couple of - little fowls - in this little house before I got married and - I remember it well, then he'd have
 a - creping, the creepers, I don't know whether it's creeping Jennies all round the wall. Oh he used to love - only a little yard, it wasn't a garden. Used to have it all around the - window sill, all round the wall. There was his couple of rabbits and h
is couple of - fowls, oh he idolized them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 How many times a week did you eat meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Meat? Well as often as my mother could get it you see, if she could afford it. That was - every day if she could afford it 'cos it used to be cheap.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Do you ever remember eating tinned meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you ever get any extra meat from these rabbits?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Rabbits? You got loose - loose rabbits. Yes, my mother used to buy loose - like rabbit, like they do now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You didn't eat the rabbits he was keeping?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Well, we - yes, my father killed one or two. And the last one, it was a big white one, Billy - we used to call it, beautiful thing. And - my mother had no dinner one Sunday and he killed this - rabbit. And that - my mother couldn't eat it. She sa
id, I'm not eating my Billy. My - I had - my mum - my dad was near to tears eating it he was but - my mother had no money to buy anything and he had to kill it. And he killed the other one or two, I'm not sure whether it's two or three he had, but - he ki
lled them, and he gradually the - the fowls - the fowls, we called 'em fowls not chickens then, he killed them in the finish. Broke his heart but there. Money you see. We never starved.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Do you remember ever seeing your mother have less food so that the rest of you could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Oh my mother went without herself for us, yes. Yes. She used to - do you know what she - I've known her to wipe the plate round - with a drop of gravy, and - tell my father she's had her dinner, she'd never had any. That
 is true. And - but I had mine and my sister had hers. She'd say, I've had my dinner. She never. She said, don't you tell your father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Would your father have more, would he be given any extra?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No, we was all shared the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Were you allowed to talk during meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. Not read papers or nothing. Not 'til we was fourteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked or did you have to eat a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No - well I was very dainty you see, my mother k
new what I wanted, she tried to get it. And even now I don't like - carrots or onions. No. And I wouldn't eat it then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What would your parents say if you left some food uneaten on the plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What would they say what? Oh never said nothing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
If there was something on the table you wanted like the salt could you ask someone to pass it to you or did you have to wait 'til it was offered?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh - we had to wait. We knew our manners.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well we never - we used to have enough at the first, we never used to get any more. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Were you expected to hold your knife and fork in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 And sit in a certain way at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes.
