\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Can you tell me how you spent Saturdays in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Like any other day Saturday was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 This is when you weren't at school, what would you do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Well play in the street. Or help my mother indoors, so - if she'd let me go out and play I used to go out but otherwise - she'd give me a little job indoors to do. But - we never had too much time in the street. Used to do little odd jobs for her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Can you remember any special games you used to play in the street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. Hide and seek like we did indoors, play with children in the street or rope. Skipping and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What about Sunday, what did you do on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 I used to go Sunday school. Sunday - my mother see I went to Sunday school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Would you wear different clothes on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes, she'd - find another frock for me to put me on but I used to keep one for schoo
l and - and she'd save one for Sunday. Never had a lot of clothes, but we kept - we was kept clean you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you play any games on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Was that because your parents thought it wrong?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 I used to stay indoors, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did your parents go to a church on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Not ever?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You say you used to go to Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Sunday school, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What church was this that it belonged to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh it was up - up Bow Road, it's all pulled down now, forget the name of it, under the arch, right up towards Bow Road used to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Would this be church of England?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Can you remember any Sunday school outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. The only outings I've had is from school, we used to go to Loughton - once a year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Were any other social activities organised by the Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No - used to have games in there you know, all the children, ordinary games but - never organised things like they do now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You didn't belong to a choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did this church run any temperance club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You weren't a member of one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you belong to any other sort of club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Was grace said at meals in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Who would say it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 My mother, she'd - always thank God you know, for meals and that, but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Were you taught to say prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh I always said my prayers, yes, I used to kneel down at the side of me bed and say me prayers. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you ever have family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did your father take an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You don't know what his views were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You can't remember who you think he'd have voted for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh he'd - vote Labour. But - you never heard him argue about po
litics, he - it was - strong Labour man you know, but he'd never get in no arguments.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What about in the early years, do you think he'd have voted for the Liberals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No. Labour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Why do you think he would vote for Labour?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 I don't know really. He had - I don't think he'd ever vote any - only Labour. I don't know why he -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Do you think your father thought that the working man had a square deal at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well I don't know much about that you see, when I was a child, I didn'
t understand things then. But I know he was a strong Labour man that's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Do you remember your father or mother voting in a general election before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No, I don't remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Do you remember your mother showing any interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No. My mother didn't bother. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You don't know if she voted in 1918 when women got the vote?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No, I remember when it was on you know, what - do you mean the - suffragettes do you mean? Yes, I remember the suffragettes but I didn'
t know much about them, I - I remember they - chained theirself to the railings and that but - we wasn't interested nothing like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 In some places at that time mend felt they risked losing their jobs if they voted differently from their employers, 
do you know if your father felt himself under that kind of pressure, to vote?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Well - don't know, my - I mean, he didn't have much work, my father at all. He was under the Tory - it was all Tories then you see, not Labour like it is now. All Tories, t
hat's why we had a - we was all lived the same, poor. A child to - there was no work no food, we - my mother couldn't - I remember when I was - three days before I was twelve - my mother bought some fish, fried fish, used to get about six or seven pieces 
f
or sixpence. Lovely it was. And I was poisoned in mine what I ate and - my father - went over Bancroft Road where Mile End Hospital is now, Board of Guardians over there, and - he went there for the doctor. And - it was like going before a judge and jury 
h
e said for a doctor. They asked all the ins and outs, so - we - so anyway he got the doctor in the finish and - Relieving Officer - what we called 'em says to my father, next time you come over here put your new suit on. My father said, if I had a new sui
t
, he said, I'd pawn it, he said, and I've have a - I'd pay for a doctor for my child, I wouldn't come to the likes of you. He told him that. And - however he came and ordered me away, I was - over at Mile End hospital, we called it Bancroft Road hospital 
then, for a - a month. They fed me well over there, looked after me, but - it was very hard, you couldn't get a doctor, you had to go before all like a judge and jury and - tell you, you couldn't get no help at all very bad. Everyone was - lived the same.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 When your parents weren't doing their work how did they spend their time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh my dad used to - go out you know, strolling round and - my mother never had much spare time. She was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Do you remember your mother having any interests outside the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 She was just so busy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Indoors, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Can you remember her ever going out to enjoy herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well on the - on a Monday - she had a few coppers so - her and a lot of women used to go out, mother's day they used to call
 Monday. And they'd dance down in the ground in the - the Building you know. They'd enjoy theirself. My mother - my mother used to play a mouth}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9052791\charrsid1926877 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 organ. And - we always knew - Monday, oh a - there's - my mother'd always have something sweet for me when I com
e home from school but - we always - knew when Monday came what to expect. No arguments or - people'd all be happy, all the neighbours you know, but my mother didn't mix up with them a lot but it was Monday they seemed to go out and have a drink together.
 
They'd put all their coppers together and they'd have this drink between them, and - they never used to get drunk, never had that money. But they'd have a - perhaps one or two drinks, come back and start dancing. Enjoying themselves. Oh - as I say they we
re very happy times on - although very hard times, but we were all happy.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What sort of dancing would they do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh - different dances. You know, ordinary - not all these dances they do now. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid9052791\charrsid1926877 C}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 oking their legs up and that. My father used to come hom
e, go right upstairs, he never took - interfered you know. 'Cos my mother - tell him mind his own business if he did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 When did your father get home from work in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 When? What time? Well depends when he - when he went you see, sometime
s he'd be home early, sometimes bit late. All depend the journeys he'd have you know. Never had a strict time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 How many evenings a week would he spend at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 How many what? Well all depends really, as I say sometimes he'd go out for a walk rou
nd and - nothing to sit indoors for really you know, my mother was always in and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did your father go to any clubs or pubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 He didn't go to the pub regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well, he didn't have much money to go to pubs. He'd like a drink if he had the money but - very seldom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did he take part any sport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did he go to the races?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did he bet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did your father or mother belong to any savings clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No boot club or sick club or funeral club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
No. Oh she'd be in an insurance you know, like they are now. You know, insurance for death - them - things. But - and she'd go in a club in a shop, you know - specially getting towards Christmas - on top of what she bought in the sho
p she'd - pay a shilling a week towards a turkey for Christmas and - like I used to do in my married life, you had to do it. And - 'cos I had it - hard through my married life but as you go back it was harder still you see, when we were children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 How did you get on with your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well I - got on all right. Yes, he was nice man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Was there one you felt particularly close to when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well he was very close to my - my - me and my sisters, my brother. He thought the world of us. Yes, he was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 As a child who did you play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What? Outdoors. Children like -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Neighbours children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Your sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well, she was older than me, she - started - you know, going out, she had a girl fri
end 'til she started courting. And - but there was only - as I say, I was the youngest, I - was at school, I was playing - when my mother let me go down. She'd say, don't you go away. We never used to wander away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Where did you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 In the ground down where we lived.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you ever go to the other children}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9052791\charrsid1926877 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 s homes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
No. No. No. I called for a girl going to school of a morning, you know, she lived nearby. But otherwise I never went in their places. My mother never had children in our place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Was there any waste ground nearby you could play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
No. No, we had a big - ground belonging to the Building you know, and it was all iron railings and we used to play there, we're safe you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What games did you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh - well al
l different, you know, we'd do skipping or - hopscotch or - or hide and seek, all that, it was all in the ground, we were - all different things. Jumping and - marbles and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Were you allowed to get dirty when you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh I used to get dirty. But - my mother used to tell me off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Were you free to play with anyone you pleased?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No, we - all the children were there, we all played together you know and no distinction.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Your parents didn't discourage you from playing with certain children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 If she - my mother liked children all to be happy together you know, play together. Not fight. She used to say, don't you fight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you belong to any youth organisations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you have any hobbies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No, no hobbies, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you keep any pets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No, not when I was a youngster, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you collect anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You didn't do gardening because you didn't have a garden?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What about fishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. I wasn't interested.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Walking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh I'd like a walk sometimes you know but - my mother - wouldn't let me go far. Case I got lost.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you have a bicycle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you take part in any sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you go to any theatres?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Or concerts, music hall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. Not when I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Or cinemas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Not when I was young. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did your parents give you any pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. Well - we'd get a farthing - get a farthing, going to school. My children used to have a ha'penny - if they were lucky. 
But that was all we could get, a farthing but - went errand for a lady we - get a farthing give us or a piece of bread and jam. But I mean the money was so scarce, that - had to look at a coin twice before we spent it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What would you spend that farthing on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well sweets. Two ounces of sweets, four ounces of - or an ounce of sweets. Some sweets used to be four or five ounces a penny. A farthings
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9052791\charrsid1926877  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 worth of sweets, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did anyone outside the home help your mother look after her house or family? No relations or friends or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 If your mother was ill or confined to bed how did she manage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well we used to do our best, she never had no one in. But my mother used to go into other people if they were ill. But - no o
ne come in to her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did your parents have any relatives living nearby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
No, not as I know of. No. I never knew. No. My - I had no grandparents, they was a dead. But a few - my mother used to have a sister over the Borough, what they called the Bor
ough, Southwark way and - oh she died when I was youngster. She had one sister over there but - otherwise - that's all the relatives I knew she had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did your parents have any friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 They didn't have people who'd drop into the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Or go to visit them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. Not as I remember, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 So you don't remember friends ever being invited into the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Perhaps on a Saturday night - a man my father knew, perhaps him and his wife'd come, but not very often. Come for a chat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Can you remember if they'd be offered anything to eat or drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Well my mother - there was always a cup of tea for anybody there. Oh yes. And if she had anything in the place it was - they was always welcome.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Would these be your father's friends or your mother's friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No, my - someone my father knew. But my mother never invited anybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 These were people from work usually, his friends from work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 I don't know - he may have been a workmate of my father's, I don't know, but I remember they used to come now and again.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did your neighbours ever come in without an invitation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. My }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4998962\charrsid1926877 mother}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 'd perhaps have her next door neighbour in on - on a Sunday have a chat, if she had time. But - but not a lot of people went - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did your parents ever go out to visit friends or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No, they didn't seem to - bother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 People often say that in those days they made their own amusements.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes - they was indoors and - and - busy doing this, that and the other you know. My mother never bothered to go out much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Many people divide society into different social classes or groups.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 In that time before 1918 would you think of some people belonging to one group and some to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You wouldn}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4998962\charrsid1926877 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 t divide society into groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You don't think there were all different groups and classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 May have been but I - I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What sort of people would you say belonged to the same group as yourself? Would you say there were working people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh they was all working class people, yes. There was - I think they was all the one type, you know, who I knew, working class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 But you think there were other classes of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well there may have been but I don't know you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another? Did you ever have to show respect in any way to anybody?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Was there ever anyone you called sir or madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No, we used to call 'em lady or - gentleman, we never used to say sir or madam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Do you remember anyone showing respect to your parents like this, calling them sir or madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 In the district you lived in who would you say were the most important people you came in contact with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 I wouldn't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What about someone like the doctor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh doctors, oh yes, but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What about shopkeepers, who would they associate with, would they have much to do with the working people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes, be sociable. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What about the clergymen at that time, were they friendly with the working people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh I expect they - yes, yes. But we - didn't see them people a lot. But - I think we were all the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Anything about teachers, do you remember who they used to be friends with, would they be quite friendly with working people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What about the employers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 I don't know much about them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 They were a group on their own were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What sort of people would you say went to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Well I only went where the children went you see, my mother - my mother went to church when she got older, you know, when she was a widow but - when we was children I don't remember her going to church.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Where - you lived did all the people in the working class have the same standard of living?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 There weren't any different groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No, all the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Can you describe a family of working people you knew, would you say that most of them lived the same sort of life as you did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 The same, yes. Some had more children - bigger families you know, but - all led the same life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You don't remember any special families who were very poor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 People who really went without?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Who had hard times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Do you think that any group felt superior to the others, did any people you know feel they were any better than the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Because they earned more or something like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 I wouldn't know. Wouldn't know - what they earned.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Were some families thought of as rough people and other people as respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh I think we was all - all the same, bit rough.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Can you remember there being an
y difference between craftsmen and labourers, people who'd served an apprenticeship and people who just did ordinary labouring?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular group? \{ILLEGIBLE\} saw herself as a working class person did she?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Can you remember anyone ever being described as a real lady or a real gentleman for any reason?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you remember seeing a policeman around where you lived as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes, we had police. And very friendly and all they were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did your mother ever threaten you with a policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
No. Oh she'd say, if you're naughty I'll tell a policeman about you, and I used to be afraid, but - otherwise the police was - you know, friendly and that. Wh
en we saw one. They - I don't think they take you like they would these - well I mean there's more going on now but - they'd say, go on, get off home and let - they knew that you'd go home and all, you know - they'd - they wouldn't run you in like they - 
w
ell they've got - I mean, it's altogether different but - we took - we - we respected the police don't you know them days and we did as we was told. We'd go home if - well not me but - other boys you know, they'd tell 'em to go home and - otherwise they'd
 come and tell your father, they'd go right home. See, they did as they was told, we - we respected our police them days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Was your home rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Rented? Yes, like a - my mother used to pay like weekly, like we do now, well we pay fortnightly now but - used to be every week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you see anything of your landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
No, not much. My mother used to - he used to ask my - like we used to have - people moved out, you could move out when you liked them days and move where you liked them days, mov
e twice in an day, if you want to, always get a place and - my mother used to let rooms, if there was a place empty - he used to say to my mother - if you can let these rooms I'll - give you a week's rent. And he never gave her the money but she'd have a 
week's free rent. Well five and six a week was a lot to her. And she'd go scrubbing rooms out. And - then if she round someone that'd have 'em she'd let them. And she'd get the week's rent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What did you feel about him as a landlord, did he actually come and collect the rent?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes. Yes. He did, yes, every door.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You said that he would do decorating and repairs, would you say he was a good landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well the landlord used to have things done you see and - but little odds and ends if people
 could them theirself, but otherwise - the landlords used to have the decorating done, well what I remember. Used to do our place up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Do you remember feeling that your parents had to struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What difference did it make to the family when your father was ill or out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Well, I tell you my mother had to - work harder and - and - couldn't get nothing anywhere, no money or - and no - used to take in more washing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Can you remember any occasions when your father was ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Oh - not a lot, he - didn't have a lot of illness, not 'til the last. But - he used to - he wouldn't lay in bed, my father. Used to go out when he was ill. He was like that for years. And - he - went to work right 'til - when he worked
 up Burdett Road - he went to work - on a - right 'til the Saturday and he was - lying dead on Monday. He worked right 'til the last, and - he had pneumonia on the Sunday and my mother had trouble to keep him in bed, he wanted to go feed his horse. He lov
ed his horse, and the other horses. And - that's before I got married. About 1918 that was. He was good - good man my father, he wouldn't give way for nothing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you ever get help from the Guardians or the - Parish or any charity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Not when I was youngster, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You can only remember your father going to the Board of Guardians for help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 That time - for that doctor, that's all. That's it. My mother never got nothing otherwise. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 When there was someone in the district whom the people disapproved of strongly was there any special way in which they showed it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No, don't think so. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Do you remember anyone being made to leave by rough music, have you ever heard of the expression 'rough music'?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Were you ever given lessons by your parents or a tutor or a governess?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No, only in school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 How old were you when you first went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 When you first started what time of the morning did you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Nine o'clock, it was - used to come ho
me at twelve. Be back by two o'clock. We used to get two hours then. Come out about - four or half past five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 So you started full time school from the age of five?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh we had to stay to the one school right 'til we was fourteen, we left on our bi
rthday. I left on the third of August, my birthday. At the one school the whoel time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Can you remember what kind of school it was? Was it a Board school or a church school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Ordinary school. No, ordinary school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 A girls school or mixed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Girls school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 How did you get to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Well - only round the back, I think the school was still there, of course I think it's modernised now, in Solbay Street, what they call Bridge Street, near - near the Bow cemetery, the school was down t
here in Albany Street and I think it's still there. We only walked - where I lived only - a little way along and that was our school. Quite nearby.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 How long did it take you to walk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh about - five or ten minutes. If I run I got there in a couple of minutes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Who went with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Oh me own. Well no doubt we met some of the children on the way you know, we'd go in and - always had to have clean boots. I know - yes - and I used to rub mine - if I never cleaned 'em, if I come out - my mother
 wasn't looking I'd rub 'em up and down me stockings, make 'em - as long as the front was clean, and we used to have - inspection every morning and look at our boots or shoes what we were wearing. Yes. And should I make 'em a bit dirty I - that's why I us
e
d to rub 'em up - used to wear the black stockings and didn't show. My mother - made us clean our boots or shoes whatever it was, sometimes we wore boots, and - and if I didn't - if I forgot to do 'em, tell you if I see a speak on it was all off by when y
ou was in school 'cos - otherwise we get the cane. We used to have a cane. Yes. Honest.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 If your appearance was wrong, if you didn't have clean shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes. Or if we done anything wrong in school - we - would get the cane. 'Cos if I got the cane, 
oh my mother used to be after me. Want to know what it's for.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did your mother take you to school when you were small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You mentioned you were in hospital when you were young, do you remember very much about that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What, when I came out of hospital?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 When you went in, what it was like in the hospital?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh it was very nice. Yes. I was in there about four weeks. And - very nice in there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you see much of the doctors, did they come round to see you every day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes. Every morning. Oh yes. Yes, they looked after me well in there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What did you have wrong with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Blood poison - food poisoning it was, through fish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you have to pay to go to the hospital?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Pay? No, well them days - I t
old you - they - my father went over and - for the doctor, but we had no money to pay, that's why he couldn't get a private doctor. That's when they insulted him. About putting on a new suit. Well my father couldn't afford - he was out of work. There was 
- no work, no food them days, not without like - as I say my mother done this bit of washing, kept us working day and night and - things was very bad then. We all lived like the same way, see. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Would people help each other if times were difficult?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Oh they were good neighbours. Yes. Yes. Very good neighbours. My mother used to go in to them and they'd come in to us, they helped one another. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Do you remember any particular people being very poor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well I - I think we were all the same. You know - there wasn't much work about and - all near enough the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What sort of jobs were paid worse than others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh I don't - I don't know about - I don't know - I mean, that age I didn't know a lot, all I knew my dad was out of wor
k anyway. But - don't know about others.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did your mother used to take you to school when you first started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Take me to school? Sometimes, 'cos - school was only just round the corner so - sometimes she'd take me but - as I got bigger I used to g
o on me own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Where did you have your midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Oh I used to come home. There was no dinners at school them days. No. Used to always come home, 'cos it was only just round the corner in Solbay Street, the school. And - used to come home every 
day 'cos my mother was always indoors, working. And then in the evening - I remember the lady were - upstairs - what was her name, Mrs Birchill, Burcher, something like that, and they used to go up - she used to have these - they used to work - she used t
o
 work for Bryant and Mays, match factory. She used to do homework. And I used to help with these boxes of matches. You know. And - I used to be up there most evenings. Never used to give me anything but - I used to go up and keep her company. Yes, being a
 
child. I remember that well. My mother knew where I was. Just like up here might be. You know. And - she - done, that woman'd get, you know, a few shillings a week, I don't know what she got but - but I used to go up there for company, to keep her - compa
ny, she were on her own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did any children have free dinners at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Visitors?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did they provide any children with free dinners?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Free - no. Not as I know of. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Can you remember any places where people could go to get food if they were hungry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. Not as far -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Not soup kitchens or anything like that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
No. No. As years went on there was places, after - while I was having my family but - not when we were little. No - well I don't think my mother'd - go if there was 'cos she was - bit of independent you know, she liked what she worked for.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 She wouldn't have wanted to take anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No. Independent she was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What did you think of school when you were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh it was all right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you like it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What about the teachers, what sort of people were the teachers at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 People what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What were the teachers like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 All right. There was a lot of young girls there as teachers. Yes. Nice. And I stayed
 there - 'til we moved you know further up Stepney. And - think it was about - thirteen when my mother moved and then I went to another school 'til - I was fourteen and left. You see, on our birthday then. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Was that a girls school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you have any men teachers at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. I never. No, was ladies.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you feel they were interested in the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes, they was interested, yes, they - they helped you know if they could. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did they used to live in the same area or did they travel in from other areas, the teachers? Did they live near the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 I don't know where they lived, I can't say. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did the teachers thing that certain things were important in life, something like good manners or tidiness, would they talk about this?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well they'd teach you manners, oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What about being punctual?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes, you had to be in exactly nine o'clock. They were very strict you know, but for our own good. But - we never played up like they d
o today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did they think about the way of speaking, did they used to try and teach people to speak properly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes. Do you know what, I couldn't speak before I was seven. No, I don't know - my mother used to tell me that - I don't know what was 
the cause of it but I remember it - I - I had a - a young girl - she had nice lovely red hair, she used to keep me in, and when the others went home and teach me to speak. When I wanted something - a slice of bread I used to give my mother the knife. And 
I'd go to the tap if I wanted a drink of water. And - one day I went home and spoke to my mother, asked her for a slice of bread, and she nearly }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4998962\charrsid1926877 fe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 ll through the floor. We had this teacher used to keep me in and teach me to speak. Only a youngster she was. And - of course my father was pleased and - oh he said, as she' gets older she'll make up for lost time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you just not speak at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. Couldn't speak a - used to make a funny noise if I wanted a drop of water or go to the tap, but - I don't
 know - don't - my mother never knew the cause of that. Her other children were all right. It was only me. But mum - there was some - words my mother couldn't say properly. I suppose that's - and that little boy I lost - years ago, I think he'd have been 
the same. Five years old he couldn't speak a lot. And yet my other children have been all right. Yes, it's funny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 And you used to stay with this one teacher?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 When you did something the teachers didn't approve of what would happen? How did they punish you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh, used to have the cane if we wasn't good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Even girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Yes, they were very - you had to do as you was told. Didnt' frighten us but we had to - be in a - our time you know and - in the afternoon and mornings and -
 yes, they used to - or - or if - they got a bit of a dunce they'd stand 'em in the corner with a dunce's hat on. Yes. Yes. Yes. 'Cos you - I mean in them days you always got one that was a bit backward or - wouldn't behave theirselves. And - as I said, t
h
ey used to look at you - shoes or boots, what we were wearing, see if they was clean of a morning. That was all for our own - benefit I suppose but - we - you know, we - had to do as we was told. Also our mothers, we had to do what they told us and - it d
oesn't hurt us, we - grew up all right. Yes. For our own benefit.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What sort of offences would they used the cane for? How serious?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well if you didn't behave yourself. You see, and - and then I remember we used to - if we was - made good attendan
ces every - every month I think it was, four weeks, we'd get a blue card. Or - or if - if wasn't late once sometimes you'd get a - a pink card, that was excellent. On your lessons and all. See, that used to encourage us, we used to get these cards. 'Cos I
 had the cane once but I wasn't perfect but I mean it was only children you know, but - they wouldn't stand old tricks them days like they do now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Would your mother be angry if you got the cane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No. She'd say - I suppose you asked for it. She wouldn't go up the school. No. I had to behave myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You can't remember what that was for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
No. No, I can't, I only got it about once. Oh you - daren't talk to anyone - in class you know. You had to behave yourself. Sit back you know at the de
sk and listen and - what they were talking about and - they come round look at your - book or papers whatever we wrote on, see if it was - got any - answers wrong or that and they - if they was right they'd put a tick you know. And - a cross if they were 
wrong we had to do it again. We had no homework. No, not them days. No homework, we came home, we was finished 'til the next morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you see much of the headmistress?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Headmistress? No, only once now and again she'd walk round. Miss Riches her name was, and - tall - elderly person she was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Were your parents interested in your schoolwork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Oh yes, they'd look you know if I took anything home and that - we used to get papers, we done all right, take home to our parents, like they do no
w. And - but they didn't take so much interest, well there wasn't so - many things going on them days like there is now, see. They'd look, just look at - my mother couldn't read or write, and my father used to look and - he'd say, that's right, you behave
 yourself. But - my mother didn't - understand it a lot. But I used to read it out to her you know. And - if I - but I mean - wasn't so much - them days - and just - learning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did your parents ever go up to visit the school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 They didn't go and meet the teachers at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
No. No, they wasn't invited - like they do now. 'Cos I've been at the school with my grandchildren when they lived up here, and had a look round, but - not them days. No. It wasn't so much going on. You just go to school and that's it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you used to have school concerts or school plays where the parents could go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No. Not as - no. No.-
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Would they have an open day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No. No. Well mine never in any case. There wasn't so much interest taken you know, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did most of the children at your school come from the same type of home as you did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh I don't know. I couldn't say. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Do you remember any very poor children who were badly dressed, did you ever come across any children
 who were not as well dressed as others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
No. We used to have one girl come in - she was always late and - she never used to get the cane, her - her mother used to send notes - with her to the teacher. And she used to have to run errands you know and that an}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4998962\charrsid1926877 d - had hardly anything on her f}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
eet. And - if she called for me going to school my mother'd give her a bit of breakfast what we had you know. And - I suppose some was a bit poorer than we were, we never had much. But my mother always - you know, sha
red with anyone, if she had it. Right 'til - she passed away. And that's how she's taught us to do the same. If there's - anyone less fortunate. And I've done it through my life. That's why I never want for anything. But I never want - my mother had a goo
d heart, she didn't have much but - people was always welcomed you know. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 How would the teachers treat children who were obviously well off, who were poorer? Did they treat them the same?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 The same as - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 They didn't suffer because they were poor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh I don't think so, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you have any gangs or groups in the school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Oh we used to - yes - girls you know and - we used to play together but - no mischief. Oh no, just playful you know. Play in the grounds and - rope 
or - hopscotch or marbles, but - I suppose there was one or two had fights, you know, but - I never used to get in trouble. No. No. But - it was all playful them days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 They didn't fight very often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. They didn't fight with me anyway. But I mea
n you always get them - children - even then - disagreeing with one another, but it wasn't much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Can you remember any children who were left out of things at school for any reason?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No, I think we were all treated the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 There wouldn't be any children in the playground who were left by themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 The next school you went to you only stayed there a year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes. Well that's - my mother moved you see. Up in Stempney. 'Cos them days you'd get a place you know - 
she had a little house there, and - she had - room upstairs, a room down and a small kitchen, five and six a - no, seven - seven shillings I think that was a week, yes. And that's where we stayed and - right 'til 1918 - '20, I got married. And - and my fa
ther died there. And I went to another school in - Whitehorse Lane.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 After that, when you'd left the other school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 So you went to three schools altogether did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No, I went to two.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 The second school was the one in Whitehorse Lane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Yes. They've got a modern school - on the same spot now. I often go round there. That way to see friends and - you know, that's where my mother lived up there and - I went to that school until - I was fourteen and - I left.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You actually left on your birthday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes, them days we left on our birthday. Yes. It's all differ}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4998962\charrsid1926877 
ent now. No fifteen and sixteen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877  then. Our - our -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 So you were fourteen when you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Fourteen, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Would you have stayed longer if you'd had the chance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 If we had chance, but we didn't have the chance see, everyone left at fourteen. Boys and all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you go to any classes afterwards, any sort of evening classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you have any regrets about your education when you look back at it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. Don't know. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Do you think you benefited from going to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Well - it didn't do us any harm you know. There's - there's a lot they - what they didn't learn at school and they learn after don't they, a lot - lot o
f children. Yes. 'Cos - we wasn't taught like they are these days. It was just the ordinary schooling you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 If your mother couldn't read and write herself she would be pleased that her children got the chance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes. Oh yes, Oh yes, we had to learn and - I was glad that we could read and write.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Had your mother been to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
My mother? Well she used to tell me that - she - in her - early - time her mother couldn't - they had to pay to go - for their children to go to school and -
 and her mother lived at Norfolk. And - her mother couldn't afford her - my mother to go to school. And that's where she didn't have the education like we had. That's why she couldn't read or write you see. And I used to - hold a pen in her hand to try an
d
 get her to write her name before she died. And - 'cos she used to have to put a cross to everything, like they do now, there's a lot of people now can't - read or write. But - no - not that - it's - can't help that, but - we've all been able to read and 
w
rite, she was pleased you know. Yes. They never had the - schools them days. They couldn't afford to send their children to school so therefore they had no schooling see. So we were lucky. Didn't have to pay when we went to school. So - as time goes on it
'
s better isn't it. Children don't realize today how lucky they are do they a lot of 'em. They are really lucky. Well I had two of my children won scholarships, my daughter in America and that one up Leicester. And - I got five pound a quarter for my girl 
i
n America. And I used to have buy uniform. 'Cos five pound them days was a lot. And a - and hat, everything. And the summer dresses I used to pay the school weekly what I could afford, for two summer dresses for her 'cos they all had dressed alike, and he
r
 blazer and that. Used to wear the big white straw hats. At - the one up Leicester - when they - offer - offered me five pound I wouldn't take it. I says, no good to me. Years after you see. My daughter in America's forty-seven now. Well that ones thirty-
t
wo, at Leicester. And five pound was no good to me, so I said, I'm not taking it, what can I buy with five pound now? Look at the price of stuff, see, as time goes on things are worse - in a way. And - so I said, but - you get the things, take that five p
o
unds off a quarter, what she needs I'll - pay you so much a week, 'cos I had other children. 'Cos she was my eighth child see. 'Cos I lost one and - so I had the others to look after so - they got everything and I paid them - weekly. She was a big girl an
d all see and I - I couldn't afford it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you do any part time jobs when you were at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Me? My mother wouldn't let me. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did any of your brothers and sisters earn money like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No. Anything we did we did for our mo
ther indoors, she wouldn't let us - earn no money like that. She'd say, plenty of time for that when you've got to work. She did all the work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What was your first full time job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 My first full time - when I - well my father wouldn't let me go to 
work before I was nearly sixteen. I remember him saying to my mother - as she's the last one and she'll stop at home and help you. And I stayed home with my mother and - in this last house, and - I helped her - not with washing, she used to do a lot of wa
s
hing then, and she used to put them all on the - we - on the - we used to have a lot of pictures, they did them days round, she'd say, we'll have new pictures tonight. And - she was happy, and - I used to do all the housework and that, the windows every w
eek and - and - my father wouldn't let me go to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you mind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Well I wanted to go to work but - yes, he - he wouldn't let me. He said, no, you're the last one - and of course my sister got married and I was the only one at home, and I used to help my mother. Then I - went out to work at sixteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What did you do then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Well I - I started in - Mile End Road in a laundry, three shillings a week. My children laugh at me when I tell them, they said, three shilling? I said, yes. And - op
posite what used to be the - what's Queen Mary's College now, I started there and - I used to take the money home to my mother. I used to get three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4998962\charrsid1926877  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 pence pocket money. And - well - buy fish and ships for a penny. Hapenny piece and a ha'porth. Yes. If you paid three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4998962\charrsid1926877  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 pence for a bit fish you was - well off. We couldn't do that. And - we lived better then than we do really now because there was more - nourishment in the food. And - I - used to give me this three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4998962\charrsid1926877  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 pence pocket money and - and after - I used to b
e on big crown irons you know with a - pipes on - and a - back breaking job and used to do the back and the fronts. And then - put 'em on a thing for the other girls with small irons, who earned more money, they had - you - like the irons in the - inside,
 you turn 'em down, they get too hot, they had little - pipes on. Well a lot of - after a while I got sixpenny rise. I give it to my mother, she give me extra three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4998962\charrsid1926877  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 pence, sixpence pocket money I had. And - well then I was there - a while and - so they - on
e of the girls on the small irons left and I took her place. So my money went up ten shillings a week, 'cos - see, we finish the shirts off then. After them on the crown irons done 'em, we finished 'em off and had to fold 'em up and - put 'em out in the a
iring - room, but they had to be inspected first with the charge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4998962\charrsid1926877 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
hand and - there was speck on 'em, throw 'em out, done 'em - do all over again, yes. And we worked - from Monday 'til - Saturday. And - I got ten shillings there. Well then I got a bit more po
cket money. I always give my mother money, always. And - well then - I heard about another job in Meredith and Drews, the biscuit people, used to be in Shadwell them days, opposite the children}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4998962\charrsid1926877 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 s hospital. And I went there. 'Cos them days you could leave o
ne job, no notice. Go to - I've been two jobs a day. Come back to the first one again. My mother never knew.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 How would you get paid for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No, we worked weekly, like so much a week. So of course I went to - I didn't say nothing my mother and
 - I went over to Meredith and Drews one Morning and fourteen and nine a week. Well that was a bit better. So - however - I started there. And - I was there a while and - putting cheese in these cheese biscuits, putting the tops on and putting them in the
 
trays. Some was on the - cheese cakes, putting the - cream and the coconut on. That was different floor. And - so when I come - I worked the end of the week and - I - and I tell my mother I've changed me job. She didn't mind. - I said, for more money. And
 
- however - I got more pocket money, I forget how much. Always - gained. And then I was there a while and - heard about - Mann and Crossman's the brewery. They was Mann and Crossman and Pawleyn then. And it's - Watney Mann's now. And - I went there. Got t
w
o pound thirteen a week. See, I was - out to better meself. And - I worked hard there. And I told my mother and - that's when I start giving her so much a week, then. 'Cos I was getting on. And - I gave her more than half. And then Christmastime we'd have
 
a guinea Christmas box give us, I used to give her that half. I was always fair to her you know. And - I was there 'til I got married. 1920. And - I went back there 'til I was seven months pregnant with my first daughter, that one who died. And - yes, we 
u
sed to - seven o'clock in the morning 'til - six at night I think it was. Used to work on the big tank. Ice - at this - ice cold weather and we had no sleeves in our blouses. And our hands used to have to go right down, right up to here, and all - chance 
a
bout empty bottles - broken down the bottom, we had to put our hand - and eight o'clock the - chill had come off the water, after the - we didn't take no notice, our arms used to be all blue with the cold, and we felt the chill about eight o'clock coming 
o
ff the water, gradually it get warmer and warmer. And - oh I've done everything up at the brewery. We had to you see and you're on the tank first and they - put you another job and - and - all the way round, you had to do something and - and - put you on 
t
hese big round machines, putting the empty bottles in, you have to smell the bottles, see if they was oily, put them to one side. Put the broken boxes - all with one pair of hands. Broken boxes somewhere else and - worked hard there. And it's all better n
ow up there. And - and that's the - my last job I had there. And then - done labe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4998962\charrsid1926877 lling. Bottling the quarts}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
 and the pints, all different labels. And they put me on that job - just before I left because I was going to give me notice in that week but they come and - spoke me, I was just going to give me notice in, I was seven months pregnant. Oh yes. But -

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 How did you get the job at the laundry, who got it for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 How I got it? Well - we used to have to enquire, you never see no advertisements abo
ut advertising jobs, and - I - used to - being a laundry I thought to myself, well it's only in Mile End Road, well it's not far from where I lived then. And - I'll go and ask, and they wanted someone. Yes. Yes. None of us earnt much money them days. We d
idn't know any different you know. I mean the - food was cheap. Had to be. And - you'd get half a loaf for a penny farthing. And - you'd get - ounce of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4998962\charrsid1926877 tea, and a - I've walked up to W}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 hitechapel many a time in Tejans, used to be the corner of Brady Street, 
well known firm it was then, and - and went up there because the tea was a bit cheaper. I've had to walk up there and get it for my mother and - you'd get a pennorth of sugar, half a pound - margarine was sixpence a pound in Whitehourse Road and it if it 
was four}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4998962\charrsid1926877  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
pence I'd get half a pound the extra ha'penny. We had no butter. And - we used to have condensed milk. And - oh we didn't starve. And - meat was cheap. My mother get two}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4998962\charrsid1926877  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 pennorth of pork rind and bones. Or a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4998962\charrsid1926877 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877  six}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4998962\charrsid1926877  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 pennorth of pieces of meat all cut
 off lovely used to be, make a big pot of stew. And - and she'd have these half quart bags of flour. And - used to last us through the week, self-raising and plain. The self-raising flour was a lovely deep yellow bags and the - plain was in white bags. An
d we had plenty of puddings, you know, and like my children}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4998962\charrsid1926877 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
s had, and - that helped to build us up you know, suet puddings, currant puddings, jam - and with jam and all that. And - we}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4998962\charrsid1926877  didn't starve. No. My mother foraged}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877  you know but - we - there was alway
s a bit of food in the cupboard. Something. But - about six pieces of fish we used to get cold for sixpence and - my mother - warm 'em up in the oven and cook a lot of potatoes and - and - we managed. I've done that for my children as well. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You said that you worked on Saturday at the laundry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Used to work Saturday then. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you get a half day during the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 A full six day week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well all day Saturday - we done a bit early Saturday, I think about twelve or one o'clock, but - never got time off in the week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you have any paid holidays? At the laundry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Never had holidays? No. If you had a half a day - if you wasn't well you had to tell 'em why. Oh we had no paid holidays. We had to work for what we got. That's what I say, things are much better now than they were then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 If you were ill for a day or two would you get paid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No. No, nothing like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you think you were paid a fair wage at the laundry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well we never - w
e never - I mean, we never - we never knew whether anyone got more 'cos when they took me on we - they told me the wage and you had to take it. You see, but - it was up to us to find out as time went on if there was any better jobs going see. Oh yes. Whic
h
 I did. I remember when I worked there - someone told me to go to Sussex, corner of New Road, and - they used to - that was a big laundry there, and - I went up there one half a day and I - I done the half day's work there and I didn't like it, I come bac
k
 to me own job, I told you my mother never knew that. I thought it'd be more money and it was all - oh it was terrible up there. So - they wanted to know why I wasn't in that afternoon. So I say oh I went about another job but it didn't suit me. So I'm gl
a
d to take - keep at this one three shilling - well, ten shillings a week - when I was on the little iron. That was hard work there but - and of course - while I worked there all my fingers opened. Every finger, and - oh it was like that, oh, quite a while
.
 And - I had to go - my mother made me go to the doctor. But like now it was sore, all red. So the doctor said to me - what do you work at? So I said, laundry. You'll have to give it up, he said. The steam. Does that. He said, you won't be no better. Oh I
 
couldn't - don't now how I worked with 'em. I had to go to work, and - so - I had to give the job up. That's how I found that biscuit - place, and - they gradually healed up bar one, and I had that for months after, but that healed up in the finish. But t
h
ey was all open the whole lot. It was due to all the steam, wet shirts, the steam all day and - affected all my - and all them years ago it's never happened, must - he said it was the steam that caused it and they'll never be better. I could hardly use me
 - hands with 'em. Every finger open, me thumbs and all opened up. Yes, well I had to go to work.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Were there accidents with burning, did people used to burn themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes. Oh I had a big burn on me arm. I went to turn round one day quick an
d a girl had - was holding the iron up, this little one. And - she had - stuff come off of felt or something, it got stuck on. She said, oh no, I went to turn round - oh it was th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4998962\charrsid1926877 
is arm, that's it, and I - I - g}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 ot it right on me arm. And then I - I slipped
 with some cocoa one morning in - in the airing room, outside that they had a great big furnace like, all red and thing right up was all red. I slipped and I just caught me arm on that - oh my - I had to go to hospital with that. Very dangerous there. But
 - I mean - in laundries it's so - better equipment, yes, yes, all different now. Yes. Yes. But - that's what my girl }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4998962\charrsid1926877 wa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
nts, ironing machine so she don't do no ironing. Two of 'em want them. Yes. But - it was hard work them days, but, as I say we had to do it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 How did you get on with the other people you worked with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh all right. Very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Had you known many of them before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No. All strangers. It's like everywhere else, you have to mix with 'em you know. Quite nice lot. 'Cos as som
e left you know - they was getting married or - or - going to - stop working, so they used to take other girls on and - quite nice we were together. We all agreed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you see much of the man who owned the laundry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. Didn't see him at all. We 
had - used to have men outside working on the big coppers you know and that and - I don't know what they they used to do out there, there used to be big coppers, I don't know what it was for but - lot of water boiling and that out there. And they used to 
k
eep the - this big thing going where the airing was, all the shirts hanging - only shirts, nothing else. Never see sheets or anything like that, shirt place it was. White shirts and - I - I know one girl there, there was a shirt there, she was told the ma
n
 was going to get married. And she starched all the bottom of it, and made it all stiff at the bottom. Oh we laughed. You know, she found out who the shirt belonged to, I don't know who it was. Yes. Oh they used to do them tricks you know, I'd say, oh don
't do that. Well, she said, he's going to get married, I'll - give him something to remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Who would have their shirts laundered then, what sort of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well I suppose - people that were better off than we were, I suppose - but we never kne
w them. There was always someone better off. Same as them days. They were - but we never knew them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You can't say you enjoyed doing this work, did you dislike doing it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No, I enjoyed all my jobs. Yes. No, I've not disliked any of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Were the hours any better at the biscuit factory?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Forget - I think - eight o'clock in the morning - I forget what time we used to finish. That was all right there. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Were you ever given any of the biscuits to take home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Not - I know what you
 mean - no, we - if we want - we could place an order. Place an order, I think it was on the Monday and - you get 'em cheap. Say what you want. I used to say, well what else is there? 'Cos I only knew what was on our floor. Cheese biscuits. And - when we 
d
idn't have much work we'd help those on - another floor with the - with the other cheese - cheese cakes. 'Cos I used to be on the biscuits, used to put that - spread that cheese in, put the tops on. Then they used to go somewhere, be wrapped up in paper l
i
ke the pubs have 'em, you know, I don't know if they have 'em now, little packets - four biscuits I think in a packet. Well we didn't do that, we used to put the cheese. Well then if we - had nothing to do, we'd help the others - on the cheese cakes. And 
-
 used to be big - great big tubs of - cream. White cream. And - I used to watch the girls, they used to show me how to just dip it in, and then put it in something else, all the ice - coconut. And then they put them on a tray. Well we used to help them - 
d
o that see. Well then, this order, and I used to say what else is there? Well - whatever cakes there were there - 'cos I didn't go on the other floors, I didn't know what they were doing - we'd - I forget how much we paid for that. We'd say how much we wa
n
ted it and - didn't come to much, about two or three shillings, and we'd have it stopped out of our money - at the end of the week, yes. And I used to bring 'em home and - oh I never took anything. No, 'cos you got to be care - my mother, oh my God. She w
ouldn't have nothing like that, my mother. No, she knew I paid for 'em. But you place an order you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 But they were cheaper than you'd buy in the shops?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes. That's why we had the chance see, we had to say what we wanted. It wasn't a lot - a
bout couple - couple of things, each things, whatever they had there, I forget what they were now, and - it all be done up for us and - stopped out of our money. And - oh cheaper than what you bought in the shop. Like now they get cheap if they're working
 on these things don't they at big factories. They place an order in and - get a bit cheaper.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Was this biscuit factory quite clean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes. Yes. Lovely and clean, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Were you given overalls to wear, - were you provided with anything like this?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. We used to have our pinafores, not overalls provided then. No. We had to - our own pinafores - we used to take.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What were the hours at Mann's brewery?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 They was - seven in the morning 'til I think it was - six o'clock at nigh
t I think it was. Long hours. But we never knew anything else. Everyone went at work long hours them days. Then there was Saturday - if they were slack - we'd go in 'til twelve, and - clear up you know, see to all the machines. Using them all the week. Se
e
 to them. Like clean 'em down. 'Cos we had like mechanics up there, if they broke, and - and - we pulled the boxes all straight, the broken ones were by theirselves or take 'em outside on he - these trolleys, go along on the wheels, and - take 'em out the
 
say and - we used to - one'd get the hose, well - we'd help hose the place down, clear, have everything spick and span - for Monday morning to start again. But if we were busy - we couldn't do that. We had to work see 'til twelve. All depended, see. And -
 oh used to - do everything you know. They taught you everything up there. So - so as if anyone was out sick we could take their place, we knew what to do you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You didn't see the owner of the brewery at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh there was a lot of owners, a lo
t of owners up there - then. Lot of owners up there then - oh a lot of - lot - men came round, you didn't know who they were. And - you could see that they was in partnership I suppose, and - they got so many wards in London Hospital, that brewery, 'cos I
 
know - still got Pawleyne ward and Corssman Ward up there and Manns and there - they was for us them wards then. Then. If we had an accident. And - I know one day a girl dropped - she was larking about, she dropped a bottle on me - finger, I don't know wh
i
ch finger, it took a lump out of me finger and they took me up there, it was only right near the hospital the brewery is, and - they - they see to it and they stitched it, but - they took me in Pawleyne Ward and - a little room there, but you could see th
e
 beds, they were there fore the - the brewery workers should they have an accident. But now - other people's in 'em now but they're still called that same name. And - I know someone - been in Bawleyne Ward, she didn't work at the brewery but they're used 
f
or other people now but they still keep the name. But them days there wasn't so many people ill - and needed all them beds like they are now. I know - they was kept for the workers, the men or women. Lot of men worked up there. And - yes, I liked working 
u
p there as well. But - I went back there twenty-seven years after I was married. But I couldn't do the work. They put me on the wheel. And I'd had a family. And - I heard they wanted someone up there and I went up and there was another charge-hand there, 
a
nd - there was a girl on this wheel, and - I mean, twenty-seven years made a difference to me, and - I was on there about half an hour, all of a sudden she called this girl away. So I thought she's coming back, but she never. So - in the evening I says to
 
this Emmy, I said, where's that girl gone? So she said - oh she's gone another job. So she said, you been - you worked here before, Mrs Willsher? So I said, yes. So she said, I thought so. I said, how do you know? She said, I've been watching you, she sai
d
 - you didn't see me, the way you handled them bottles. You picked four up a time you see. You smell 'em and - no, and we were - like this all day long. 'Course - guess how my body was. Like this. And - you mustn't let no holes go by. There's about a doze
n
 or more. And it's full of holes don't you know, and - you've got to keep 'em going. And - so - on the tank where I used to work when I was single there was three or four young girls there larking about. They didn't work like we used to work. And - so of 
c
ourse when she says she'd been watching me, I said, look Emmy, I can't keep this going on my own. So I said, you'll have to get me help. I said, I've had a family since, so - she didn't - of course one morning - these girls larking about, didn't care abou
t
 their work - and I put a oily in for - and I let some holes go by. So one come round, she's about sixteen, so she said, here lady, she said - you put oily bottle in the machine. So I says, so what? So she said - you know if Emmy - knows that, she says, s
h
e'll give you three days off for her convenience. I said, oh will she? As well as she can give me three days I'll take three days for home convenience, I said, besides you carry on there and mind your own business, you do your work. I worked on there twen
t
y-seven years ago, before you were thought of. I said, and we worked - them days. And earlier and all in the morning. I said, so don't you come round talking to me like that, I said. So she didn't say no more. And - so I kept it going, I stayed there seve
n
 weeks. And I fell ill. And - I couldn't do the work, it was no use, that big wheel. I did when I was single. Yes. And I still had to put the - and you have to put the crates on the - rollers, keep on the move at the side, broken ones were put over there,
 
and - and when I was single we used to have the men put all the - all the bottles, crates of bottle behind you, and as you go further back they put more near you. But not when I went back, they didn't do that, I had longer walk - journey, picking 'em up, 
p
utting 'em in the wheel, putting - sorting the bottle - the broken boxes, and - so of course they used to go in the toilet and have their beer, the men, used to get drunk. We daresn't have any. We used to get a lovely dinner there for eight pence up in th
e canteen. When I was single. When I was single, yes. Eight \endash  eight pence dinners. Beautiful. Yes. And - they used to take a - drink of beer, but I never 'cos - I never did care for drink.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You were allowed to drink some beer if you fancied it were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Only if you - if you're not caught. Instant dismissal. If they catch you - but the men - they knew the men drank, and yet the men used to - be allowed to take home so many quarts. A night. And - some of the girls used to take it home but I shut me 
eyes, nothing to do with me, I never got in trouble. Let them do what they like. But I daresn't take any home to my mother, no fear. Oh she wouldn't tolerate that. She used to like to buy her own, three ha'pence a pint if she needed it. And - however I - 
I
 fell ill and - and I says to my daughter who's in America now I said, I can't go back there. So - the following week I was to go up for me cards, they wouldn't give 'em to her. So she - Emmy said - the charge-hand she said, oh you're mum's got the 'flu. 
S
he said, mum's not got the 'flu, it's this hard work here. She couldn't - 'cos all over me body like this all day and - Saturday and all, oh my God. Well seven weeks I mean I was never lazy but I couldn't do it, I couldn't hold up. So however - time went 
o
n and I sent her back and I - with a note to say that if - they - she don't hand my cards in - I'm going somewhere about it. She give 'em to her. 'Cos they're supposed to hand 'em in to the - yes, I got them, yes, and - oh I couldn't go back there again, 
a
nd - it was - the work was the same if you know what I mean but - I was older. Twenty-seven years older and had a family, I couldn't do it. And of course the money - I forget that the money was, it was a lot more. Oh yes. Five or six pound a week or somet
hing. But I couldn't - do the work then, it was - and I - she wouldn't give me a - easier job because she see - I could do that well. But I couldn't keep - it going, it was impossible, not all the time. Seven weeks was enough for me. There.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Is this the only job you did when you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 That was my last job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you do any other jobs while you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 When I - no. No, well I had children you see when I left there. My husband wouldn't let me go, he said, you've got enough to 
do at home here. Which I did you know, we only had two rooms.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 But that was after the second world war when you went back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 When - I got married - yes. I got married in 1920 and - well then - we couldn't - oh we got a place over - one big room - c
ouldn't get a bigger place - over Bethnal Green. And - we used to pay - well there was so many families living in this big house, and we used to pay the rent to a man there, supposed to be the landlord. And after a few weeks he was missing, him and his wi
f
e, we heard that she - they was living together, and they hopped off with the money, our money. So - when the proper; landlord came we all had to get out in twenty-four hours. Through no fault of our own. And my father-in-law had two rooms and he - he wen
t in his kitchen and the back room as we used to call 'em, back rooms, and he had a little scullery at the back, and - he let us have his front room. And - that's where my first child was born there. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Looking back would you have preferred to do any other type of job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No, I've been satisfied with what I've done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you belong to any trade union at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 A trade? My father was in trade - in the coal - coal porters union, my dad. He was always a coalie, 'til he got that job up at
 Burdett Road, he fell ill - and he couldn't do much work and - but he didn't - he got that little job up Burdett Road and he - didn't get much money. And he had that 'til he died. But - he used to tell me - he - 'cos my mother used to have big - big fram
e
 with a big photo in, trade - coal - Coal Porters Union. And my father belonged to that. He used to pay tuppence a week. Union money. Then it went up to four pence. My husband used to pay four pence. But - that's all I knew my father belonged to you see. 
But that little job up there, he only had that 'til he - passed away. But - but he was always a coalie, my dad. He had men working for him.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What is a coal porter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well - what - coal Porters Union. Well - well - it's all on the coal. Nothing else
. All for coalmen you know, them days. 'Cos my father was always a coalie, he used to tell me up - in Aldgate used to run up the big buildings, always been big buildings up there, Wentworth Street, used to - cart the coal right up there. Yes. Worked very 
hard, my father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 He delivered it with a horse and cart?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Then later when you were a child you remember him delivering timber?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 He got - he got up Burdett Road and - with this one - horse cart and - used to - give my mother
 a golden sovereign, I used to remember him putting it on the table for her week's wages. She had five and odd rent, five and six rent to pay out of that. But we managed you know, we had to. You've got to manage these days, well so we managed them days. M
y mother - never go in debt. No. She wouldn't have that worry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 So you didn't belong to any trade union yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No, I don't belong to anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you feel that employers and workers had different interests at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes. Yes. Yes, we seemed to have got appreciated, you know, them days for our work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 By employers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you think there was any division of interest between workers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh I don't know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Do you think there was a difference between people who were craftsmen and people who weren't craftsmen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh I didn't know much about -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Because they may have done some sort of apprenticeship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No. Didn't know much about them people. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Your family didn't know of any skilled workers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Do you think that when you started work it changed your attitude to life in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No. Always been the same. Happy go lucky you know. I've never craved for anything as long as I've - got a job of work I was satis
fied. Even now I don't crave for anything, as long as I can just manage. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you go on living at home when you started work at the laundry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes. Right 'til I got married, yes. And then father died you know and - he died about two years 
before I was married, about 1918 he died, yes, sixty odd he was, sixty-three. And my mother lived to seventy-one. 'Course I was married then, had three children when she passed away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 When you started work do you think it changed your attitude towards your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Were you able to do more things and go out more or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
I used to go out - a bit more you know, as I got older. My mother - let me go out with a girl friend you know. Until we started courting. But my husband I knew 
from a child. And - I fell in the cart with marrying him but still, it's a gamble you have to take you know how they change. Yes, I knew him - when I went to live with - where his father let us have that one room, well - I lived down there - my mother liv
e
d in one of them houses nearby - before she went to this last house. Only a little while. 'Cos we could move where we wanted to them days, move twice in a day if you wanted to, my mother-in-law did. That's - I wasn't married, but she used to tell me. Yes,
 
I knew my husband and - his mother lived in the - many years in this house where I went to live when I got married. And - he used to come down - and this last house my mother had - where we lived 'til I got married - well, he - he - he used to come down t
h
at street - or the street playing a tin whistle, getting a couple of coppers. And - his mum only had two boys, my husband was the eldest one, and he had a younger brother, and - he used to get a couple of coppers, and - and - used to come out fairly early
 
and - I used to see him walking with his dad and then his father'd go home and - get something for his breakfast so as he could go to school. That's just how it was, him and his brother. And of course I got to know my husband from a child, you know, child
.
 And - as time went on I was working - so I went to - I could - could never get rid of him you know. As you get older. He was about seventeen months older than me. And - I'd go - used to be a fair in - Mile End Road. We used to call it the fair or - pictu
r
es and - all roundabouts and all, used to be a girl - two girls come out, Daisy and - oh I forget the other one's name, come out twice nightly and dance on the stage outside, we'd all gather round watching. And everywhere I went I'd look round, he'd be be
h
ind me. Yes. And - and then perhaps I'd - go and queue up for the pictures, get an hour and a quarter for a penny, Charlie Chaplin's films, all - silent films. And - I'd - queue up, and I'd forget all about him. He'd be behind me. He'd get to the - pay bo
x
 before me, put my penny down. And then - I wouldn't talk to him, and - we'd come out and I'd be with a girlfriend and - I used to say to 'em before I go home I'm going to the fish shop in the same street, Erley Street, get a big piece and a ha'porth, lov
e
ly. I'd go in there, when it got my turn, you know, we never queued up, we'd just go in and - get served and - might be one or two in there. And - as I put my money down someon'ed put the money down before me, and I knew it was him behind - honest. Oh I h
a
d that ages, it seems I had to have him. Lovely fellow. And - and then - of a Saturday might be going there, he'd say, don't you take no money for the lady, he'd say - I'll pay for that, he'd get me a three penny bit and a pennorth. Big lovely lump of fis
h. I'd get the three pence. I'd say, thanks, and I'd walk off, I couldn't stand him.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You didn't talk to him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Couldn't stand him, no. I couldn't stand him. Well after a while - he disappeared. His mother - still lived there. And I never went roun
d to her. She didn't know - she was blind you know, dear old soul she was, and his father was - almost blind. And - she never knew me so - he disappeared. As time went on - someone told me that he - joined the Army, and - he went to Ireland. And - he came
 home a couple of times, I dodged him, I see him in a green - uniform. Got a lovely fellow, he had very fair ginger hair, that's how my children\rquote 
s ginger some of 'em. And - big built fellow. And I dodged out of his way. Well then - he must have gone back. I
 heard he was killed. So - I was sorry you know, treating him like I did. I wouldn't have nothing to do with him. Of course - as time went on - my mother belonged to a loan club in Roma Road and I used to walk right down there, it was a long walk but we d
i
dn't notice it, me and this girl friend, I went round to her one Monday night and - it was every Monday I had to take it, and - this Jessie said, come in. So I always went in. I don't know why but I said, no I don't want to come in. So I stood there waiti
ng for her to get ready and I were like this and all of a sudden I see two fellows coming up in the road, one was a sailor and the other one was in khaki. Long trousers, he used to ride - horse ride \endash  horse ride \endash 
 horseback ride, he used to wear the breeche
s sometimes with 'em. He was very smart. So - got nearer. I said, oh hello Ian. 'Cos I heard he got killed. So - oh he was smashing. I know - he had his eyes was on me. Funny how I didn't go in that house that Monday night. It wasn't dark. They come right
 
over to me, he said, hello. So he shook hands, so - I - began to like him, I don't know why, you know, to know that he was alive. So - he said, you going out anywhere. I said, yes, I'm going to Roma Road. I shouldn't have told him. I'm going to Roma Road,
 
pay my mum's club - it was only a shilling a week - loan money. So he said, can I come with you.? So I said, if you like. So however, he said something to this fellow. I said, no you go with him. So he said, no. So this fellow went, this sailor. And - thi
s
 Jessie came out and - he walked down there with me. Wasn't half smart. Of course - he was home for a few weeks, so - oh I said, I didn't expect to see you any more. So he said, I know what you heard, he said, I was killed. So - he said, I heard all about
 
that, he said, but I'm - very much alive, so anyway he come down there with me and - well then I worked at the brewery. He asked me where I worked. So he said, I'll come round in the morning, take - take you to work. This went on for about three or four w
e
eks you now. And - come round on morning, my mother used to shout down, who's that? Oh it's only a friend of mine. So - I used to take a cup of tea up, wouldn't tell her it was a fellow. And - anyway - he got a cup quick and we'd go to work and - he'd com
e
 and meet me in the evening and - just before we finished off the girls used to look out as though they had someone to wait for 'em. And they come in - they'd say, 'ere, ain't half a smashing fellow out there, I wonder who he's waiting for. Well I thought
 
to myself oh my God. I never said nothing. They never asked me. So - anyway, oh what's - who went out with - it was me. And he'd shake hands and kiss me as though - of course I'd known all them years but I didn't get - didn't go with him long. And - oh we
 
used to go for walks and that, very nice you know but - had a - he was a lady's man. He used to work for the officers you know and - officers batman and - go about with officers dances and that, he was very gay. 'Cos he was lovely looking you know. And - 
a
 lot of my children take after him you know, big built and that. And - as time went on I wished one of 'em had had him. I had a bit of a life with him, but that was the only thing - women you know, I had two separations. But - when he died I was away from
 him seventeen years, but he -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 So you were engaged for quite a long time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Well to tell you the truth he sent me the money home to buy the ring, 'cos from Silonica you know - and - I forget how long we was engaged. Decided to get married when he 
come home. I couldn't get out of it. Oh but often sit and think you know. And I suppose it still happens in some cases - now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 When you started work at the laundry how did your brothers and sisters treat you, did they treat you any differently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Only had one brother, no. Good to me. Yes, good to me and my sister he was, and she went to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What about Sundays once you started work, did you spend Sunday any differently?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Indoors. Well about -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 After you went to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes, oh - went out - I went out with a girlfriend you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you stop going to Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh yes, when I - left - when I started working and that, but we had to go while we were at school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you go to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No, I didn't go to church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 So on Sundays you'd go out with friends, go out for walks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you take an interest in politics yourself at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you have any views on politics at all yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. No, was never mixed up in politics
. I never used to hear my father talk about politics. Only but he knew he was a - used to vote Labour, but he never used to talk about politics and - we never. No, it wasn't - interested in 'em then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Do you remember voting in any general election before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh - no, no. No, only after I was married you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What party would you have voted for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Oh the same, Labour. Always been Labour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You weren't a member of any political party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 You didn't take any interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No, no interest in 'em. I don't interest myself now in politics much. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What would you do with your spare time once you were at work, how would you spend your evenings?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Well I'd go to the pictures or that you know. And that. Oh g
oing - go out with a girlfriend or that. I never mixed with a crowd you know. We used to make our own - pleasure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you go out in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Sometimes, not a lot you know. Liked to sit indoors and have a read.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 But if you went out you'd go to the cinema would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Cinema, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Anything else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Music halls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No, never used to go anywhere else. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Would you visit friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No, we didn't - have many friends you know to visit. I mean, we didn't visit f
riends like you do now. No, everyone seemed to be in their own places you know and they didn't seem to invite anybody like they do now. People never had much - what they had they wanted theirselves, they - it wasn't 'cos they were greedy but they couldn't
 afford it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you make any new friends at this time, different people than you'd known at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
I only had one - one girlfriend, I had her, she was like a sister, lived opposite my mother. And - I never had a proper friend after that, when sh
e - she lived - a good many years but - I say courting you know, that parted us. I was the start - first one to start courting and - she met her husband - after that and - he turned out worse than mine. And she lived - she worked over - Charrington's brew
ery. She lived a good many years, I used to meet her and - have a chat with her and - and she went in bad health and she - died. But she was the only real friend I did have when I was young you know, before I - while I was at work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did you go to her house and would she come to yours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Yes, she - she'd sleep with me in my house one weekend and I'd - I'd go and sleep with her. She was a nice girl. She was the only true friend I - we was more like sisters you know. My sister used to go out 'cos she - 
had a young man, who she married, and - so I had this - girl in my house and I'd go in her place. But - just for to keep one another company. And her mother was like my mother, worked hard when she was alive. All had to work hard.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What would you two do together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Oh - oh we'd go perhaps - cinema, well we used to call 'em pictures then, not cinemas. We'd go there and - or we'd go up the theatre. Tuppence. Up - used to go the - what's the A.B.C. cinema in Mile End Road now, it was the Paragon. And 
we'd go there. Or the Forresters in - Cambridge Heath Road. Or the Pavilion up - in Whitechapel. Used to be there, opposite Whitechapel church, go up there. Yes, we'd go up in the gallery for tuppence, tuppenny rush, up the stairs. And yet there was never
 any trouble. Boys and girls they all used to go - a lot of 'em we never knew, we kept ourself to ourself. But there was never any trouble.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No gangs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 No. Well there was no trouble if there was so - perhaps you'd see three or four fellows together
 but you wouldn't see any fights or that like you would now, no. No one inter - interfered with us. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 They didn't have as much money as young people have today did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes. Don't know the value of money. As for pocket money, we - we never - 
my children never had pocket money - like my grandchildren get now. They all get pocket money. But - I don't know - and yet ; we grew up better. And my children. With less money. That's the trouble.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Would your parents expect to know where you were if you went out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 
Oh yes, my mother knew - wanted to know where I'd been, yes. I daresn't be out late, but you know what, you're asking me that, do you know right - right to the time - right 'til I got married I wasn't allowed - allowed out after ten o'c
lock. That is true. My children laughed at me when I told 'em, I wouldn't let them out too late, but - they have been out later than that. Ten o'clock, and - we was courting and my - and my dad died, and - my mother was more after me then when he - 'cos h
e
 was nice, my dad. And they - he passed away and of course them days we used to keep in - black six months, and then go in half mourning for another six months. Yes, a twelve month. And - we went - used to be - a theatre, the corner of here, Stainsby Road
 
in the main - main road, and - we called the Princes Theatre, and - we always went first house to be home - before ten. So one night my husband said, oh, he said, you can't live with the dead, he said - you're dad's been dead for some time now, come secon
d
 house. Oh, I said, no, my mother - kill me. However - took a chance. I was twenty-three when I got married. But I tell you I was twenty-odd when it happened. And we went there. And I could see ourself now - we come out, nearly eleven o'clock. So - we run
 
right along Burdett Road, wouldn't wait for a - bus. I said, my mother 'll kill me, I was nearly crying. A young woman. Got home. My mother's waiting behind the door for me. As I - as she's opened the door - my husband happened to stand at the corner, he 
k
new how frightened I was. She got hold of my hair, she has, pulled me in road and half beat me. My mother. I was late. The God's truth. But I - 'course I - being me mother I couldn't hit her back. We respected our mother. We daresn't answer back, never mi
n
d anything else. It was only 'cos - I never had a father. 'Cos it would never have happened if my father - wouldn't let her - you know, he'd say, leave her be, but he - so - anyway my husband run down and he - pulled me away from her, he said, leave her a
l
one, he said. She's nearly twenty-two, he said, she's allowed to be out. Not while she's here she's not, and, she said, you mind your own business. She said - she's not going to be out after ten o'clock, not while she's at home with me. She was good mothe
r, but - she was strict. - However - I got married at twenty-three.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Did your father like your future husband? Did your mother like him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 I mean - he, no, he didn't meet him a lot, but - my father liked his mother of a Monday to come round to have
 dinner with us. 'Cos she was blind, she was - only little. And - I - I worked at the brewery and - I - my mother used to go round for her or someone go round for her, bring her home, every Monday, have dinner. He liked her. And 'cos she was blind and she
 
was very jolly, very - always - laughing she was. And - she had to come round every Monday, have dinner with us. Yes, he liked her, but he didn't like his father a lot, my father you know. Was a bit - oh I don't know - nasty man, but - I got on all right 
with him when we got married 'til he died, and - so, but his mum, he did like her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Were there many foreign people around here when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 What round - what where we lived? No. See a few coloureds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 When you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Yes. W
ell - 'til the time I got married we had a - coloured woman but we was - neighbourly with her. Yes. There was a few coloureds, not like now. Now and again you'd see a - a - my husband bought a coloured man home once - a young man. And I found out his moth
e
r-in-law lived that - that - woman where my mother lived opposite, she - was coloured, we found out that was his mother-in-law. Yes, the children was throwing at him, stones and - cut his face, my husband bought him home, only a young man. He married her 
d
aughter. And when he said who she was, oh, I said, her mum lives opposite my mother. And - yes, he bought him home and - he see to his face, nice fellow he was. And - I wasn't a - I've never been against the coloureds, no. All people are together. Well ma
y
be - I mean some of our as bad. But we're all human beings and - we've got to learn to live with one another, they speak to me, I speak to them. And - but my husband was like that, he - but - it's all wrong today, they're one against the other. We can't h
e
lp what we're born as. I'm sure - when my little boy - who died at five in the road accident when he was - quite a baby he was in Mile End Hospital, and - he used to scream if I left him. And this - one day this coloured man came in, very - and he had his
 
little baby next to mine. And they used to give my baby - you know - he was very nice, and he used to come and visit us. I see people look but I didn't care. My husband was there, 'cos he was coloured you see. Well - there wasn't many coloureds, not like 
there is now. But I've never been against 'em. We've had 'em all round here but they're moved now, 'cos they're building. Got 'em in here.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5533424 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 Were there many Jewish people in your area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1995491 JW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13377328\charrsid1926877 English, oh yes. Oh Jewish? Well - we didn't have a lot but th
ey was mostly up Aldgate way, all up that way and like there is now. But - whoever they were we used to get on all right but - not where my mother lived, no, they're all English people. But I suppose there was some Jewish people living in different street
s but we didn't know 'wm. My mother was glad to washing for the Jewish people you know. 'Cos they was - always used to put their washing out.
\par }}